âœ… PART 1 â€” NOTES (Concepts Covered: SQL Constraints & Data Integrity
ðŸ”¹ Common Types of Constraints
Here are the main constraints discussed:
Constraint	Purpose / What it does
PRIMARY KEY	Ensures each row is uniquely identified. No duplicate or NULL values allowed in that column (or combination of columns).
UNIQUE	Ensures all values in a column (or set of columns) are unique â€” no duplicates.
NOT NULL	Ensures a column cannot have NULL (empty) values â€” every row must have a value.
FOREIGN KEY	Links a column in one table to the primary key of another table â€” enforcing referential integrity (valid relationships between tables).
CHECK	Allows specifying a condition that values in a column must satisfy (e.g. age > 0).
DEFAULT	Provides a default value for a column if no value is specified on insert.

ðŸ”¹ Why Constraints Are Important
They keep data consistent, valid, and meaningful â€” prevent duplicates, missing values, invalid references.
Help enforce relationships between tables â€” e.g. ensuring an order belongs to a valid customer.
Avoid logical/data errors â€” e.g. disallowing NULLs in mandatory fields, preventing duplicate user IDs.
Makes database more reliable, easier to maintain and query.

ðŸ”¹ How Constraints Are Defined
Constraints are set when you CREATE TABLE, by specifying rules after column definitions.
Some can also be added (or altered) later using ALTER TABLE.
Using constraints is better than manually checking data on application logic â€” database does the enforcement.

ðŸ“ PART 2 â€” EXAMPLES (SQL Table Definitions & Use Cases with Constraints)
Below are example table definitions and data operations illustrating common constraints.
âœ… Example A â€” Defining a Table with PRIMARY KEY, NOT NULL, UNIQUE
CREATE TABLE Users (
    user_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    username VARCHAR(50) UNIQUE NOT NULL,
    email VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
    age INT,
    created_at DATE DEFAULT CURRENT_DATE
);

What this does:
user_id uniquely identifies each user (no duplicates, no NULL).
username must be unique and cannot be empty (NULL).
email cannot be NULL.
created_at will default to todayâ€™s date if not provided.

âœ… Example B â€” FOREIGN KEY Constraint (Referential Integrity)
Assume we have another table Orders linked to Users:

CREATE TABLE Orders (
    order_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    user_id INT,
    order_date DATE NOT NULL,
    amount DECIMAL(10,2),
    FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES Users(user_id)
);


What happens:
user_id in Orders must match an existing user_id in Users â€” you cannot have an order for a non-existent user.
Prevents orphan orders and maintains relational integrity.

âœ… Example C â€” CHECK Constraint & DEFAULT
CREATE TABLE Products (
    product_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    product_name VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
    price DECIMAL(8,2) CHECK (price >= 0),
    status VARCHAR(20) DEFAULT 'active'
);


price cannot be negative (must be â‰¥ 0).
If you donâ€™t specify status on insert, it defaults to 'active'.

âœ… Example D â€” Inserting Data (Respecting Constraints)
Valid insertion:
INSERT INTO Users (user_id, username, email, age) 
VALUES (1, 'alice01', 'alice@example.com', 28);
Invalid insertion (will fail):
INSERT INTO Users (user_id, username, email) 
VALUES (2, 'alice01', NULL);

â€” fails because username must be unique (alice01 already used) and email cannot be NULL.

âœ… Example E â€” Trying to Insert Invalid Foreign Key
INSERT INTO Orders (order_id, user_id, order_date, amount) 
VALUES (100, 999, '2025-12-03', 150.00);

â€” fails because user_id = 999 doesnâ€™t exist in Users (violates FOREIGN KEY constraint).

âœ… KEY TAKEAWAYS & Best Practices
Always define PRIMARY KEY to uniquely identify rows.
Use NOT NULL for mandatory fields (e.g. name, email).
Use UNIQUE for columns that must be distinct (e.g. username, email).
Use FOREIGN KEY to link related tables and enforce relationships.
Use CHECK and DEFAULT to enforce valid data and defaults automatically.

Constraints help reduce errors, ensure data validity, and simplify application logic â€” rely on database constraints rather than manual checks when possible.
